Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Observations:¶

The DataFrame has 9 columns as mentioned in the Data Dictionary. Data in each row corresponds to the order placed by a customer.

  • order_id, customer_id, cost_of_the_order, food_preparation_time and delivery_time are numerical
  • restaurant_name, cuisine_type, day_of_the_week, and rating are categorical
  • In the rating column, we can see that there are some "not given" values that will likely have to be addressed/cleaned in order to analyze data appropriately.
  • "day_of_the_week" is a little misleading, where the data appears to only be broken into weekday and weekend, instead of identifying each individual day of the week.
  • It may be advantageous to combine food_preparation_time and delivery_time into another column in order to get an idea of the 'total time' it takes for a customer to place the order and have the food arrive.
  • restaurant_name and cuisine_type appear to be self explanatory. It appears to be the restaurant name and the respective type of cuisine associated with the food order.
  • Considering the data is based on New York, cost_of_the_order is likely in dollars.
  • Customer_id may be unique to each person or generated per order. Will be good to determine this.
  • Although it is not stated, the order_id's are likely able to be ordered in a time series of sorts. The problem is we do not have a general timeframe or code decipher for the id (does not appear to be Julian). It would be good to ask the data provider this question to understand the trends over times or seasons.

# It would not be wise to remove that much data from the entire data set, as most of the columns do appear to have useful data.
# We are making a copy of the dataframe
dfrm=df.copy()
#we are 'removing' all the 'not given'(s) in the new dataframe
dfrm.drop(dfrm[dfrm['rating'] == 'Not given'].index, inplace=True)
#reseting the index after dropping the 'not given's
dfrm=dfrm.reset_index()
#changeng the data type of rating to integers for numerical data analysis
dfrm['rating']=dfrm['rating'].astype(int)
#verifying the result
print(dfrm['rating'].unique())

[5 3 4]

Observations:¶

  • Although there is no technical missing data in the form of NaN/null points. "not given" in the rating column will inevitably prevent us from analyzing the data set to its full potential. Particularly if we wanted to perform statistical analysis numerically, or moreso, objectively.

  • 'not given' was presented 736 times out of 1898 ratings, which is approximately 40% of the data. This is a large chunk of the data, so it would not be wise to "drop" each of these rows in the original set of data.

  • For now, we will create a separate dataframe called "dfrm" and analyze this data separately

  • In addition, we will convert the object into an integer (int), so we can analyze the rating data numerically/objectively, e.g. determining the mean rating for a given restaurant, etc.

Customer ID¶

One thing to note is that the count vs. the final or max customer ID number is significantly different. A couple questions to potentially ask the client is, does the customer ID number have more meaning then what it appears, such as, part of the number is a designation for location (in the city) or time?

However, what is more likely the case is that we recieved a snapshot of a single city, as we know our data is from New York. The total number of customer ID's could be spread across the US for example.

Still it is important to understand the distribution.

What is interesting is the data is somewhat 'bimodal' with two peaks. One around 75,000, and a much smaller peak around 375,000.

This could very well be an indicator of a surge due to a promotional offer. For instance, perhaps there was an offering when the app first came out. Then, some time later, another promotional offer of a smaller proportional.

There is a big drop in what me may be able to consider 'new customers', and this may very well be due to a multitude of reasons. However, a potential talking point with the client. Note, alternatively, there could be a number of customer's using the app often, and perhaps there is some saturation.

Food Preparation, Delivery Time, & Customer Wait Time¶

By comparing the food preparation and delivery time. We can see that the average time (mean) is relatively close between the two variables. With food preparation time, average a couple minutes longer. As we put these two variables together in "customer_wait", we can see that time it takes from placing an order to the customer receiving it. This also shows us that there is a relatively wide range of time it takes for the customer to place the order and receive it.

What may be interesting data is if we had time of day. Does rush hour play a role? Such as, increase the delivery time? Do more orders come in during regular eating periods in the day and cause the preparation time to go up?

Also, do some restuarants have a larger area for which they deliver too?

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [222]:
# created a new column in the dataset of net revenue created by orders greater than $20 / multiplied the values by 25%
df['revenue_order_25%'] = 0

df.loc[df['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, 'revenue_order_25%'] = df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25

# created a new column in the dataset of net revenue created by orders less than or equal to $20 and greater than $5 / multiplied the values by 15%
df['revenue_order_15%'] = 0

df.loc[(df['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (df['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20), 'revenue_order_15%'] = df['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15

# summated the individual revenues in order to understand which orders are more profitable overall.
revenue_25=df['revenue_order_25%'].sum()
revenue_15=df['revenue_order_15%'].sum()

# added the revenues together in order to determine the total
total_net_revenue = revenue_25 + revenue_15

print("The net revenue created by order's greater than $20 is: $", revenue_25)
print("The net revenue created by order's less than or equal $20 and greater than $5 is: $", revenue_15)
print("Total Net Revenue: $", total_net_revenue)

The net revenue created by order's greater than $20 is: $ 3688.7275
The net revenue created by order's less than or equal $20 and greater than $5 is: $ 2477.5755
Total Net Revenue: $ 6166.303

Observations:¶

The total net revenue generated by the company across all the orders is $6166.30.

There is more revenue generated by orders that are greater than $20.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

  • As seen in the exploratory data noted by customer_count, there is a very large proportion of customers that only use the application once (784 customers)

  • Shake Shack has the highest number of orders out of any other restaurant (219). The Meatball Shop (132), Blue Ribbon Sushi (119), and Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken (96) also have a fairly large proportion of the total orders.

  • American (584 orders) and Japanese (470 orders) food appear to be the preferred cuisine for customers with Italian (298 orders) and Chinese (215 orders) a near 3rd and 4th.

  • The vast majority of orders occur on the weekend (1351 orders) and much fewer during the weekday (547 orders)

  • Customers tend to wait longer on the weekday (mean = 55.6 mins) compared to weekend (mean = 49.9 mins) days even though there are fewer orders.

  • A large proportion of the ratings are not given (approximately 40%)
  • A greater net revenue is made by Foodhub on orders that are greater than 20 dollars (3688.73 dollars total) compared to less than or equal to 20 dollars and greater than 5 dollars (2477.58 dollars total) over the time period of the dataset.

Recommendations:¶

  • From a data exploration perspective:

    • Perhaps, rating could be broken into additional categories to better understand the customer experience, such as:

      • cost
      • service
      • quality

    • Considering there were timestamps used to produce the delivery/preparation time data, these timestamps could potentially be helpful to understand the busy parts of the day or if there is any seasonality to the orders.

      • Further on this note, peak times could be used as a means to adjust delivery pricing (similar to companies like Uber). Also, confirmation that potential peak times for traffic are effecting delivery times. Even though outliers were not necessarily discovered.
      • Understanding the delta between the preparation time, pick-up time, and delivery time should be considered. Realistically, a delivery driver may not always pick-up the order on time and when it is ready. This data is hidden somewhere in the prep time or delivery time.
      • Further, with a potential date with the timestamp, we could understand potential fluctuations with day of the week. The category is relatively broad at this point (is Sunday greater than Saturday?, etc.).
    • Understanding the demographic of who are actual residents of New York vs. potential travelers using the app would be good to understand.
    • We may also want to understand the devliery radius allowed for each restaurant and how the driver's are selected. Do they have a maximum distance from the restaurant? It would be helpful to further generate solutions for reducing delivery time safely.
    • It is odd that the customer rating system goes from 3-5. Is there anymore data that we could use to see the full picture?

  • Understanding why there are so many single use customers is important. Continuous use is an important part of sustaining revenue and continuing to build the top line. Using feedback in the rating system may help or feedback through a promotional offer may be a good approach.

  • Considering Weekend orders are so high in comparison to Weekday and order costs are the same between the two. It may be advantageous to add a premium for weekend orders and perhaps a deductions for Weekday orders to generate more revenue on the weekends and develop more customers during the weekdays.

  • Although rating did not necessarily show a correlation with customer wait time. It may still be advantageous to focus on reducing customer wait time to help improve the customer experience and improve the repeatable use of the app. Giving restaurants incentives for reducing preparation time and giving delivery drivers incentives for delivering the food sooner (while still being safe) is potential avenue.

  • There is a vast number of 'not given' ratings. Providing incentives/promos for improving the order rating frequency would help to further provide information and accuracy in determining the differences between lower rated and higher rated customer experiences.

  • Restaurants such as Shake Shack and the The Meatball shop have a high number of customer orders, while their price is near the center of the pack on average. Understanding what is driving more orders is important. This could be because of general food quality or favorite cuisine demographic, but understanding this and potentially sharing it with other restaurants may improve overall revenue longer term.

  • American and Japanese food are the cuisine types with the highest orders, while this may be do to availability of product or favorite cuisine demographic, it is imperative to develop a marketing strategy to either continue to promote top cuisine categories to boost sale. Or, attempt to understand how these cuisines perform better in order to influence other cuisine types that are less ordered.
